eryday life into citizenship and nationalism and how labor class poets and artists recorded and resisted the burden of this new biopolitical life. The author reveals how the frictions of material life work over and against designs by the state to form a unified biopolitical Britain. At its most radical, this book changes what constitutes the central concerns of the Romantic period and which texts are valuable for understanding the formation of a nation, its agriculture, and its rural landscapes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAnimals in art. 0aAnimals in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismx19th century. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFarm life in literature. 0aHuman-animal relationships in literature. 0aRomanticismxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aArea Studies : British Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438465692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438465692/original  a978-3-11-149102-8  SUNY Press eBook Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles